The following initial steps have been recommended by the INDI and Temple Street hospital:1. Sustainable Government funding for the evidence based Temple Street hospital W82Go! treatment programme for children who are clinically obese;
2. co-ordinated and sustainable funding of an evidenced based community treatment programme such as Up4it! that will be rolled out nationwide over a targeted time period that builds capacity through multi-stakeholder delivery partnerships and utilisation of local engagement models and resources [We know that is what works];
3. appointment of a national post for obesity management to co-ordinate the clinical service delivery of obesity treatment in an integrated pathway between hospital and community [A big problem is the lack of integration in order to be able to grasp the nettle; Ireland is a small country but could be a poster boy like the Aquitaine region in actually starting to show reductions];
4. consistency in delivery of treatment services using service frameworks, referral pathways and professional staff with performance management and evaluation;
5. engagement of the Government and the HSE with the clinical experts working with children such as consultants, dietitians, physiotherapists and psychologists in the development of a co-ordinated, integrated pathway for the management of obesity.As outlined at the Taoiseach's launch of Healthy Ireland, we want to see a whole-system approach to improving population health and well-being that includes the goals of increasing the number of people who are healthy at all stages of life and reducing health inequalities. We need to start with the most vulnerable who need treatment right now. I thank the committee for its time.
